data.your-first-test-object#Your First Test O:
Let‚Äôs take a simple User class to work with:
import dev.agiro.matriarch.Mother; // Define a simple class public class User { private String name; private String email; private String role; private int age; // Getters and setters... } create a simple test object using Matriarch:
User randomUser = Mother.forClass(User.class).build(); That‚Äôs it! Matriarch will automatically populate all fields with random, valid data.

data.circular-dependencies#Circular Dependenc:
Matriarch detects and handles circular references:
public class Parent { private List<Child> children; } public class Child { private Parent parent; // Circular reference } // Matriarch stops recursion to prevent stack overflow Parent parent = Mother.forClass(Parent.class).build(); // parent.children will be populated, but child.parent will be null Best Practice: Design your test objects to avoid circular dependencies when possible, or use excludeFields():
Parent parent = Mother.forClass(Parent.class) .excludeFields("children[*].parent") // Exclude back-references .build();

data.issue-circular-reference-stack-overflow#:
Cause: Bidirectional relationships.
Solution:
// Exclude back-references Parent parent = Mother.forClass(Parent.class) .excludeFields("children[*].parent") .build();

data.issue-null-pointer-exceptions#Issue: Nul:
Cause: Nested objects or collections not being populated.
Solution:
// Ensure collections have elements Order order = Mother.forClass(Order.class) .withCollectionSize(1, 5) // Guarantee at least 1 item .build(); // Or exclude problematic fields Order order = Mother.forClass(Order.class) .excludeFields("optionalMetadata") .build();

data.issue-slow-test-execution#Issue: Slow Te:
Cause: Generating too much data.
Solution:
// Use smaller collections Mother.forClass(Order.class) .withCollectionSize(1, 3) // Instead of default 1-15 .build(); // Or use streams for large datasets Stream<User> users = Mother.forClass(User.class) .buildStream(10000);

data.issue-type-conversion-errors#Issue: Type:
Cause: Incompatible value types.
Solution:
// Wrong - string to int fails .forField("age", "not a number") // Correct - proper type .forField("age", 30) .forField("age", "30") // Also works - auto-converted

data.attributes#Attributes:
RandomArg[] args() Array of @RandomArg annotations defining test cases.
Example:
@ParameterizedTest @MotherFactoryResource(args = { @RandomArg(targetClass = User.class), @RandomArg(targetClass = User.class, overrides = {...}) }) void test(User user) { ... }

data.attributes-1#Attributes:
String name() default "" Descriptive name for test reports.
Example:
@RandomArg(name = "Admin User", targetClass = User.class) Class<?> targetClass() Required. The class type to generate.
Example:
@RandomArg(targetClass = User.class) OverrideField[] overrides() default {} Array of field overrides.
Example:
@RandomArg( targetClass = User.class, overrides = { @OverrideField(field = "email", value = "test@example.com"), @OverrideField(field = "role", value = "ADMIN") } ) String jsonOverrides() default "" JSON string for complex nested structures.
Example:
@RandomArg( targetClass = Order.class, jsonOverrides = """ { "orderId": "ORD-123", "customer": { "email": "test@example.com" } } """ )

data.attributes-2#Attributes:
String field() Required. Field path (supports dot notation).
Example:
@OverrideField(field = "address.city", value = "New York") String value() default "" Value to set or regex pattern.
Example:
@OverrideField(field = "email", value = "test@example.com") OverrideType type() default OverrideType.STRING Type of override.
Example:
@OverrideField(field = "email", value = "[a-z]+@test\\.com", type = OverrideType.REGEX) boolean isRegex() default false Shorthand for type = OverrideType.REGEX.
Example:
@OverrideField(field = "email", value = "[a-z]+@test\\.com", isRegex = true)

data.attributes-3#Attributes:
int collectionMin() default 1 Minimum size for generated collections.
Example:
@MotherConfig(collectionMin = 5) int collectionMax() default 15 Maximum size for generated collections.
Example:
@MotherConfig(collectionMax = 10) boolean jsonOverridesWin() default true Whether JSON overrides take precedence over array overrides.
Example:
@MotherConfig(jsonOverridesWin = false) long seed() default 0L Reserved for future deterministic generation.
String knownPatterns() default "" Not yet implemented. Use patterns.yaml instead.
Example:
@MotherConfig(collectionMin = 5, collectionMax = 10) class MyTest { @Mother User user; @Test void test() { ... } }

data.attributes-4#Attributes:
OverrideField[] overrides() default {} Array of field overrides.
Example:
@Mother(overrides = { @OverrideField(field = "email", value = "test@example.com") }) User user; String jsonOverrides() default "" JSON string for complex structures.
Example:
@Mother(jsonOverrides = """ { "email": "test@example.com", "role": "ADMIN" } """) User admin; Usage:
@MotherConfig class MyTest { @Mother User defaultUser; @Mother(overrides = @OverrideField(field = "role", value = "ADMIN")) User adminUser; @Test void test1() { // Fields populated before each test assertNotNull(defaultUser); assertEquals("ADMIN", adminUser.getRole()); } @Test void test2(@Mother User paramUser) { // Parameters injected assertNotNull(paramUser); } }

data.configurablesuppliert#ConfigurableSuppli:
Base class for suppliers that need constructor parameters.
public abstract class ConfigurableSupplier<T> extends RandomSupplier<T> Example:
public class IntegerRangeSupplier extends ConfigurableSupplier<Integer> { private final int min; private final int max; public IntegerRangeSupplier() { this(0, 100); } public IntegerRangeSupplier(int min, int max) { this.min = min; this.max = max; } @Override public Integer get() { return randomInt(min, max + 1); } }

